    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-12-19T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-12-19T05:00:00-05:00" n="196"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d196">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A4B/588: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-12-19T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 19, 1934—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 19—7:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>280. This morning the Privy Council in Plenary Session gave unanimous approval to
                    the Government’s decision to abrogate the Washington Naval Treaty and so advised
                    the Emperor. The draft instructions to Saito,<note n="12" xml:id="d196fn12"
                        >Hirosi Saito, Japanese Ambassador to the United States.</note> I
                    understand, will be submitted to the Cabinet <pb facs="0370" n="274"
                        xml:id="pg_274"/> either December 21 or 22, but when the formal notice will
                    be conveyed to the Department is not yet decided.</p>
                <p>It is my impression that Hirota desires to delay, if possible, the formal notice
                    of abrogation until after the adjournment of the present conversations in London
                    in order to avoid the charge that they were disrupted by Japan’s action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
